   Administration on Aging -
   _____________________________________________________________________

   Flash

Latest News:  On August 8, 2001, Josefina G. Carbonell was sworn in as
Assistant Secretary for Aging.  Her nomination was confirmed by the Senate on
August 1, 2001.
   _____________________________________________________________________

   Previous:

   AoA News Flash of July 26, 2001:
   Josefina G. Carbonell's nomination to be Assistant Secretary for Aging
   in the Department of Health and Human Services was unanimously approved
   by the Senate Committee on Health, Education, Labor and Pensions on
   July 25, 2001. The Senate is expected to vote on final confirmation
   shortly.

   Excerpts from Previous White House Releases  (6/8/2001):
   The President has nominated Josefina Carbonell to be Assistant
   Secretary for Aging.  She is one of the founders and is President and
   CEO of the Little Havana Activities and Nutrition Centers of Dade
   County, and serves as part of the national technical assistance team to
   the Office of Refugee Resettlement.  Carbonell served on the Board of
   Directors of the National Committee to Preserve Social Security and
   Medicare in Washington, D.C., and she held positions on numerous
   national, state and local commissions and boards. She attended Florida
   International University and received the Kellogg Fellowship in Health
   Management from the Kennedy School of Government.
